I"πí<h2 id="mission-5-by-an-stm">Mission #5 by an STM</h2>

<blockquote>
  <p>In other cases though, say (when you are organizing information and
providing solutions) [1] - based on that - to your boss, you might
want to (be like Tiger Woods, conscious, controlled and not
automatic)[2]‚Äù</p>
</blockquote>

<p>You‚Äôve described [2] using a lovely concrete example in the <a href="/DP-CT-examples.html">last
post</a>. However, [1] is sorely lacking in examples. What is this
‚Äúorganizing information‚Äù? Or ‚Äúproviding solutions‚Äù? That could be
anything from ‚Äúit‚Äôs hot today‚Äù all the way up to ‚Äúe = mc^2‚Äù. Contrast
that to PG‚Äôs <a href="http://www.paulgraham.com/vwplan.html">business plan</a> for his startup in 1995:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>OVERVIEW Webgen allows clients to generate web catalogs remotely.</p>

  <p>There are several other companies that can generate and serve web
catalogs. The best known site of this type is Marketplace MCI
(www.internetmci.com). But while these other sites use their
generators in-house to build catalogs from materials provided by
clients, Webgen‚Äôs generator can be used interactively by anyone with
a modem and a copy of Netscape. ‚Ä¶</p>
</blockquote>

<p>You might want to describe what you‚Äôre doing in such terms, like
‚Äú<em>generate web catalogs remotely</em>‚Äù or ‚Äú<em>used interactively</em>‚Äù, so that
it is clear even to an outsider what you‚Äôre doing.</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Mission #5:</strong> Time to chunk it up. Right now, you are working on
sentences and paragraphs at a time. That is, you get feedback about
your output dimensions after writing the entire paragraph (or God
forbid, the entire essay). The feedback isn‚Äôt immediate enough
(principle #3 from TiO). In contrast, look at how I narrowed down the
specific phrases [1] and [2] where you gave examples or not.</p>

<p>You need to take passages you feel you don‚Äôt understand clearly
(perhaps some things you‚Äôve written yourself about important yet
unclear issues in ‚Äúrationality‚Äù and some outside material about tough
technical problems), mark within parentheses each important phrase
like I did with [1] and [2], check if you‚Äôve given an example for it,
and if not, rewrite it with a concrete example. If you‚Äôre not sure if
a phrase is important or not, err in favor of an example. 200
repetitions should be a good start. Soon, you will come to notice
immediately if you are throwing out words without any concrete
example, the way a misspelled word in an editor shows up with red
underlines.</p>

<p>Does it mean that PG and EY will give examples after every phrase? Not
necessarily. But they will have an example in mind as they write. I
suspect that when we say ‚Äúpeople don‚Äôt think clearly‚Äù, we mean that
their words don‚Äôt correspond to any concrete example (see: ‚Äúcritical
thinking‚Äù). And when your words don‚Äôt correspond to anything concrete,
you can make them say anything. For a striking example, check out this
philosophical passage that EY tore to pieces:
https://youtu.be/D6peN9LiTWA?t=1067</p>

<p>What was the problem there? The words didn‚Äôt correspond to any known
piece of reality. They were figments of the poet‚Äôs imagination, and
yet he thought they described something real. It sounded convincing
even to me. I was like, yeah, maybe we really are fallen people
compared to those wise, brotherly ancients.</p>

<p>How would you and I tackle that? We would stop at the first phrase in
the first sentence: ‚ÄúIn the age when life on Earth was full‚Äù. Ok. Give
me a historical example or empirical evidence for what you mean by
‚Äúlife on Earth was full‚Äù. People had AC‚Äôs? Cars? Long lives? Lots of
sex? (Could be true. Could also be not true. Need empirical
evidence. And if you say you can‚Äôt get that evidence from millenia
ago‚Ä¶ well, that‚Äôs the whole point! Why are you using as an example
something that you have no real evidence about? End of story then and
there.)</p>

<p>Let‚Äôs take another example closer to home. ‚ÄúI need to practice
critical thinking and become a master.‚Äù - Anonymous, 1785 AD. Well,
Mr. Anonymous, what is this ‚Äúcritical thinking‚Äù you speak of? Let‚Äôs
see at least one example (after you‚Äôve practiced on a bunch of other
sentences).</p>

<hr />

<h2 id="goal-and-how-to-do-it">Goal and how to do it.</h2>

<blockquote>
  <p><strong>Mission</strong>: You need to take passages you feel you don‚Äôt understand
clearly (perhaps some things you‚Äôve written yourself about important
yet unclear issues in ‚Äúrationality‚Äù and some outside material about
tough technical problems), mark within parentheses each important
phrase like I did with [1] and [2], check if you‚Äôve given an example
for it, and if not, rewrite it with a concrete example. If you‚Äôre not
sure if a phrase is important or not, err in favor of an example. 200
repetitions should be a good start. - an STM via e-mail</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>Goal</strong>: All fluff words (like problem solving, critical thinking)
have to be associated with examples. And we need to do this on 200
phrases.</p>

<p>The first example is given below‚Ä¶</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>‚Äú(I want to get better at <em>critical thinking)</em>‚Äú[1]- Anonymous 1795 AD</p>
</blockquote>

<p><strong>P:</strong> I want to get better at ‚Äúcritical thinking‚Äù.</p>

<p><strong>E:</strong> In the article on <a href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/2ftJ38y9SRBCBsCzy/scope-insensitivity">scope insensitivity</a> there is a
lot of discussion about how to design experiments that distinguish the
‚Äúprototype-dominated‚Äù affect and the warm glow of moral
satisfaction. I don‚Äôt understand this. There is a whole discussion and
I am finding it hard to wrap my head around it. I‚Äôd like to get better
here.</p>

<p>At work, I am having to do quite some ‚Äúproblem solving‚Äù. By that I
mean I am given a couple of observations (about leak in the Vacuum
Chamber). I need to isolate what is the problem is (is it leaking from
outside? or are these virtual leaks? etc‚Ä¶), I need to design
experiments (pump down the chamber and measure leak) and I need to
convey the results (make a presentation and explain how my diagnosis
is right). This is hard for me, I want to become better here, i.e., I
often find myself banging my head to make sense of what is happening
and presenting it. :)</p>

